    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "active_lock_reason": null,
    "body": "When a Confluence page containing a table is read via the FUSE mount and written back, table cell alignment attributes are silently dropped during the ADF→Markdown→ADF round-trip.\n\nExample: a page with a 3-column table:\n\n| Header A | Header B | Header C |\n|----------|----------|----------|\n| left     | center   | right    |\n\nAfter `cat page.md > page.md` (no-op edit), the `colwidth` and `align` ADF attributes are gone. The table still renders in the Confluence UI but alignment is reset to the default (left).\n\n**Root cause:** `adf_to_markdown` discards `attrs.align` for `tableCell` nodes; `markdown_to_storage` has no alignment syntax to restore them. This is a known limitation of the Markdown←→ADF translation layer.\n\n**Fix:** Preserve `attrs.align` in a HTML comment (`<!-- align:right -->`) appended to the Markdown cell, and strip+restore it on the write path. Alternatively, document the limitation and accept it.\n\n**Resolution:** Documented as accepted limitation in CHANGELOG `[v0.6.0] ### Known Limitations`. ADF table alignment is out-of-scope for the Markdown round-trip; use the Confluence UI for alignment changes.",
